\par The walk led through a dust-excluding lock port into a tool bunker, gray walls punctured by outlets for transmission tubes, the inevitable computer controls blinking, ticking, chuckling, whirring.\~ The place smelled of a sweet oil.
\par As the port clanged shut behind the Durants, a figure came from their left and sat on a padded bench across from them.
\par The Durants stared silently, recognizing and repelled by the recognition.\~ The figure's outline suggested neither man nor woman.\~ It looked planted there in the 
seat, and as they watched, it pulled thin cables from pockets in its gray coveralls, plugged the cables into the computer wall.
\par Harvey brought his attention up to the square, deeply seamed face and the light gray eyes with their stare of blank directness, that coldly measured observation which was a trademark of the Cyborg.
\par "Glisson," Harvey said, "you summoned us?"
\par "I summoned you," the Cyborg said.\~ "It has been many years, Durant.\~ Do you still fear us?\~ I see that you do.\~ You are late."
\par "We're unfamiliar with this area," Harvey said.
\par "We came carefully," Lizbeth said.
\par "Then I taught you well," Glisson said.\~ "You were reasonably good pupils."
\par Through their clasped hands, Lizbeth signaled }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "They're so hard to read, but something's wrong."\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 She averted her
 eyes from the Cyborg, chilled by the weighted stare.\~ 
No matter how she tried to think of them as flesh and blood, her mind could never evade the knowledge that such bodies contained miniaturized computers linked directly to the brain, that the arms were not arms but prosthetic tools and weapons.\~ 
And the voice -- always such a clipped-off unemotional quality.
\par "You should not fear us, madam," Glisson said.\~ "Unless you are not Lizbeth Durant."
\par Harvey failed to repress the snap of anger, said, "Don't talk to her that way!\~ You don't own us."
\par "What is the first lesson I taught you after you were recruited?" Glisson asked.
\par Harvey brought himself under control, forced a rueful smile onto his mouth.\~ "To hold our tempers," he said.\~ Lizbeth's hand continued to tremble in his.
\par "That lesson you did not learn well," Glisson said.\~ "I overlook your fallibility."
\par Through their hands, Lizbeth signaled, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "It was prepared for violence against us."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Harvey acknowledged.
\par "First," Glisson said, "you will report on the genetic operation."\~ There was a pause while the Cyborg changed its jacked connections to the computer wall.\~ "Do not be distracted by my work.\~
 I distribute tools -- thus" -- it indicated the bunker -- "this space which appears on }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 their }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 screens as a space filled
 with tools, will never be investigated."
\par A bench slid from the wall to the Durants' right.\~ "If you are fatigued, sit," Glisson said.\~ The Cyborg indicated its cable linkage to the wall computer.\~ "I sit only that I may carry on the work of this space while we speak."\~ 
The Cyborg smiled, a stiff rictus to signify that the Durants must realize such as Glisson did not feel fatigue.
\par Harvey urged Lizbeth to the bench.\~ She sat as he signaled, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Caution.\~ Glisson's maneuvering us.\~ Something's being hidden."}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Glisson turned slightly to face them, said, "A verbal, factual, complete report.\~ Leave out nothing, no matter how trivial it may seem to you.\~ I have limitless capacity for data."
\par They began recounting what they had observed of the genetic operation, taking up from each other on cue without a break as good couriers were taught to do.\~ 
Harvey experienced the odd feeling during the recital that he and Lizbeth became part of the Cyborg's mechanism.\~ Questions came so mechanically from Glisson's lips.\~ Their answers felt so clinical.\~ He had to keep reminding himself, }{
