By eight A.M., the streets and speedwalks of Seatac's industrial district-north swarmed with machine and foot traffic -- the jostling impersonals of people following the little strung-out channels of their private concerns.\~ 
Weather control had said the day would }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 be }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 held to a comfortable seventy-eight Fahrenheit with no clouds.\~ 
An hour from now as the day settled into its working tempo, traffic would become more sparse.\~ Dr. Potter had seen the city at that pace many times, but he had never before been immersed in the shift-break swarm.
\par He was aware that the Parents Underground had chosen this time for its natural concealment.\~ He and his guide were just two more impersonals here.\~ Who would notice them?\~
 This didn't subtract, though, from his fascinated interest in a scene that was new to him.
\par A big female Sterrie in the green-white striped uniform of a machine-press operator in the heavy industry complex pushed past him.\~ She looked to Potter like a B2022419}{\lang1033\langfe1049\super\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 K}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 G8 cut with cream skin and heavy features.\~ In a gold loop in her right ear she wore a dancing doll breeder fetish.
\par Almost in lock step behind her trotted a short man with hunched-up shoulders carrying a short brass rod.\~ He flashed an impish grin at Potter as they passed, as much as to say:\~ "Here's the only way to get through a crowd like this."
\par Porter's guide turned Potter aside onto the step-down walk and then into a side street.\~ The guide was an enigma to Potter, who couldn't place the cut.\~ The man wore a plain brown service suit, coveralls.\~
 He appeared reasonably normal except for a pale, almost sickly skin.\~ His deeply set eyes glittered almost like lenses.\~ A skull cap concealed his hair except for a few dark brown strands that looked almost artificial.\~ 
His hands when they touched Potter to guide him felt cold and faintly repellent.
\par The crowd thinned here as the step-down walk rounded a corner into a byway canyon between two towering windowless buildings.\~ There was dust in this cavernous street rising up and almost concealing a distant tracery of bridges.\~ 
Potter wondered at the dust.\~ It was as though the director of local weather allowed dust here in an unconscious passion for naturalness.
\par A bulky man hurried past them and Potter was caught by the look of his hands -- thick wrists, bulging knuckles, horned callouses.\~ He had no idea what work could cause such deformity.
\par The guide steered them now onto a succession of drop walks and into the cave of an alley.\~ The swarm was left behind.\~ A feeling of detachment seized Potter.\~ He felt he was reliving an old and familiar experience.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Why did I come with this person? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he wondered.
\par The guide wore the wheeled blazon of a transport driver on his shoulder, but he'd said right out he was from the Parents Underground.
\par "I know what you did for us," he'd said.\~ "Now, we will do something for you."\~ A turn of the head.\~ "Come."
\par They'd talked only briefly after that, but Potter had known from the first the guide had correctly identified himself.\~ This was no trick.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Then why did I accept the invitation? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Potter asked himself.\~
 Certainly it wasn't for the veiled promises of extended life and instant knowledge.\~ There were Cyborgs behind this, of course, and he suspected this guide might be one of them.\~ 
Most of the Optimen and Servant Uppers tended to discount the Folk rumors that Cyborgs did exist, but Potter had never joined the cynics and scoffers.\~ He could no more explain why than he could explain his presence here in this al
ley cave walking between dark plasmeld walls illuminated by the ghost flicker of overhead glowtubes.
\par Potter suspected he had at last rebelled against one of the three curses of their age -- moderation, drugs and alcohol.\~ Narco-pleasures and alcohol had tempted him in their time .\~.\~. and finally moderation.\~ He knew it wasn't normal for the times.\~
 Better to take up with one of the wild sex cults.\~ But pointless sex without even the faint hope of issue had palled on him, although he knew this for a sign of final dissolution.
\par The alley opened into one of the lost squares of the megalopolis -- a triangular paving and fountain that looked to be real stone, green with the slime of ages.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 The Optimen don't know about this place, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Potter thought.\~ They despised sto
ne which eroded and wore away -- in their time.\~ Regenerative plasmeld was the thing.\~ It stood unmoved and unmoving for all time.
\par The guide slowed as they reached the open air.\~ Potter noted a faint smell of chemicals about the man, oily sweetness, and a tiny scar running diagonally down the back of his neck into his collar.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Why didn't he try to blackmail me into coming? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Potter wondered.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Could he be that sure?\~ Could anyone know me that well?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par "We have a job for you," the guide had said.\~ "An operation you must perform."
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Curiosity is my weakness, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Potter thought.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
That's why I'm here.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par The guide put a hand on Potter's arm, said, "Stop.\~ Wait without moving."
\par The tone was conversational, calm, but Potter felt hidden tensions.\~ He looked up and around.\~ The buildings were windowless, faceless.\~ A wide door stood out in the angle of another alleyway ahead.\~ 
They had come almost around the fountain without encountering another person.\~ Nothing stirred or moved around them.\~ There was only the faint rumbling of distant machinery.
\par "What is it?" Potter whispered.\~ "Why're we waiting?"
\par "Nothing," the guide said.\~ "Wait."
\par Potter shrugged.
\par His mind veered back to the first encounter with this creature.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 How could they know what I achieved with that embryo?\~ It must be the computer nurse.\~ She's one }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 of }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 them.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par The guide had refused to say.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 I came because I hoped they could help me solve the mystery of the Durant embryo, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he thought.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 They were the source of the arginine intrusion}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295  -- }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
that's what I suspect.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par He thought of Svengaard's description -- a contrail-like intrusion.\~ It had deposited arginine-rich sperm protamine through the coiled alpha-helices of the embryo's cells.\~ 
Then had come the operation -- the cysteine masked, neutralized with sulfhydryl and the ATP phase .\~.\~. oligomycin and azide .\~.\~. the exchange reaction inhibited.
\par Potter stared up at the patch of blue sky framed by the buildings around the square.\~ His mind, concentrated on the Durant cutting, had encountered a new idea.\~ He no longer saw the sky.\~ His awa
reness was back within the swarming cell structure, following the mitochondrial systems like an undersea hunter.
\par "It could be repeated," Potter whispered.
\par "Silence," the guide hissed.
\par Potter nodded.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 On any embryo at all, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he thought.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 The key's the arginine flooding.\~ I could duplicate that myself on the basis of Sven's description.\~ Gods!\~ We could make billions of Durant embryos!\~
 And every one of them self-viable!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par He took a deep breath, dismayed by the realization that -- with the record tape erased -- his memory might be the only container of that entire operation and its implications.\~ Svengaard and the computer nurse could have only part of it.\~ 
They hadn't been }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 in }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 there, immersed in the heart of the cell.
\par A brilliant surgeon might deduce what had happened and be able to reproduce the operation from the partial records, but only if he were set the problem.\~ Who would ever take up this problem?\~ Not the Optimen.\~ Not that dolt Svengaard.
\par The guide tugged at Potter's arm.
\par Potter looked down into that flat, chill-eyed face with its lack of genetic identification.
\par "We are observed," the guide said in an oddly depersonalized tone.\~ "Listen to me very carefully.\~ Your life depends on it."
\par Potter shook his head, blinked.\~ He felt removed from his own person, become only a set of senses to record this man's words and actions.
\par "You will go through that door ahead of us," the guide said.
\par Potter turned, looked at the door.\~ Two men carrying paper-wrapped parcels emerged from the alley in front of it, hurried around the square opposite them.\~ The guide ignored them.\~ Potter heard a babble of young voices growing louder in the alley.\~ 
The guide ignored these, too.
\par "Inside that building, you will take the first door on your left," he said.\~ "You will see a woman there operating a voicebox.\~ You will say to her:\~ 'My shoe pinches.'\~ She will say:\~ 'Everyone has troubles.'\~ She will take care of you from there."

\par Potter found his voice:\~ "What if .\~.\~. she's not there?"
\par "Then go through the door behind her desk and out through the adjoining office into a rear hall.\~ Turn left and go to the rear of the building.\~ You will find there a man in a loader supervisor's uniform, striped gray and black.\~ 
You will repeat the procedure with him."
\par "What about you?" Potter asked.
\par That is not your concern.\~ Quickly, now!"\~ The guide gave him a push.
\par Potter stumbled toward the door just as a woman in a teacher's uniform emerged from the alley leading a file of children between him and the bolt hole.
\par Potter's, shocked senses took in the scene -- children, all dressed in tight shorts that revealed their long flamingo legs.\~ They were all around him suddenly and he was bulling his way through toward the door.
\par Behind him, someone screamed.
\par Potter lurched against the door, found the handle, looked back.
\par His guide had gone around to the opposite side of the fountain which concealed him now from the waist down, but what remained visible was enough to make Potter gasp and freeze.\~ The man's chest was bare revealing a single milky
 white dome from which blazed a searing light.
\par Potter turned left, saw a line of men emerging from another alley to be crisped and burned down by that searing light.\~ The children were shouting, crying, falling back into the alley from which they had emerg
ed, but Potter ignored them, fascinated by this slaughter-machine which he'd thought was a human being.
\par One of the guide's arms lifted, pointed overhead.\~ From the extended fingers, lancets of searing blue stabbed upward.\~ Where the light terminated, aircars tumbled from the sky.\~
 The air all around had become an ozone-crackling inferno punctuated by explosions, screams, hoarse shouts.
\par Potter stood there watching, unable to move, forgetful of his instructions or the door or his hand upon the door's handle.
\par Return fire was coming now at the guide.\~ His clothing shriveled, vanished }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 in }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
smoke to reveal an armored body with muscles that had to be plasmeld fibers.\~ The ravening beams continued to blaze from his hands and chest.
\par Potter found he no longer could bear to watch.\~ He wrenched the door open, stumbled through into the relative gloom of a yellow-walled foyer.\~ He slammed the door behind him as an explosion rocked the building.\~ The door rattled behind him.
\par On his left, a door was flung open.\~ A tiny blue-eyed blonde woman stood there staring at him.\~ Potter found himself oddly recognizing the markers of her genetic cut, reassured by the touch of humanity in these tiny betrayals.\~ 
He could see the cabinet of a voicebox in the room behind her.
\par "My shoe pinches," Potter said.
\par She gulped.\~ "Everyone has troubles."
\par "I am Dr. Potter," he said.\~ "I think my escort has just been killed."
\par She stepped aside, said, "In here."
\par Potter lurched past her into an office with lines of empty desks.\~ His mind was a turmoil.\~ He felt shaken to his roots by the implications of the violence he had just witnessed.
\par The woman took his arm, herded him toward another door.\~ "Through here," she said.\~ "We'll have to go into the service tubes.\~ That's the only way.\~ They'll have this place surrounded in minutes."
\par Potter stopped, figuratively dug in his heels.\~ He hadn't counted on violence.\~ He didn't know what he had expected, but not that.
\par "Where're we going?" he demanded.\~ "Why do you want me?"
\par "Don't you know?" she asked.
\par "He .\~.\~. never said."
\par "Everything'll be explained," she said.\~ "Hurry."
\par "I don't move a millimeter until you tell me," he said.
\par A raw street oath escaped her lips.\~ She said, "If I must I must.\~ You're to implant the Durant embryo in its mother.\~ It's the only way we can get it out of here."
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "In }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 the mother?"
\par "In the ancient way," she said.\~ "I know it's disgusting, but it's the only way.\~ Now, hurry!"
\par Potter allowed himself to be herded through the door.
