Where the last skyway ended, the van took the turn away from the undermountain tube, and held to the wide surface track on the Lester by-way.\~ 
It led upward through old tunnels to the wilderness reserve and breeder-leave resorts along an almost deserted air-blasted roadbed.\~ There were no slavelights up here, only the moon and the stabbing cyclops beam of the van's headlight.
\par An occasional omnibus passed them on the down-track, the passenger seats occupied by silent, moody couples, their breeder-leave ended, heading back to the megalopolis.\~ If any of them
 focused on the van, it was dismissed as a supply carrier for the resorts.
\par On a banked curve below the Homish Resort Complex, the Cyborg driver made a series of adjustments to his lift controls.\~ Venturis narrowed.\~ Softness went out of the ride.\~ Turbines whined upward to a near destructive keening.\~ 
The van turned off the roadbed.
\par Within the narrow box that concealed them, Harvey Durant clutched the bench with one hand and Lizbeth with the other as the van lurched and bounced across the eroded mounds of a
n ancient railroad right of way, crashed through a screen of alders and turned onto a game track that followed the right of way upward through buck brush and rhododendrons.
\par "What's happening?" Lizbeth wailed.
\par The driver's voice rasped through the speaker, "We have left the road.\~ There is nothing to fear."
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Nothing to fear, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Harvey thought.\~ 
The idea appeared so ludicrous he had to suppress a chuckle which he realized might be near hysteria.
\par The driver had turned off all exterior lights and was relying now on the moon and his infrared vision.
\par The Cyborg-boosted vision revealed the trail as a snail track through the brush.\~ The van gulped this track for two kilometers, leaving a dusty, leaf-whi
rling wake to a point where the game trail intersected a forest patrol road -- a cleared track matted with dead sallow and bracken from the passage of the patrol vehicles.\~ 
Here, it turned right like a great hissing prehistoric monster, labored up a hill, roared down the other side and to the top of another hill where it stopped.
\par Turbines whined down to silence and the van settled onto its skids.\~ The driver emerged, a blocky stub-legged figure with glittering prosthetic arms attached for its present needs.\~ 
A side panel was ripped off and the Cyborg began unloading cargo, tossing it indiscriminately down through a stand of hemlock into a deep gully.
\par Within their compartment, Igan lurched to his feet, put his mouth near the speaker-phone, hissed, "Where are we?"
\par Silence.
\par "That was stupid," Harvey said.\~ "How do you know why he's stopped?"
\par Igan ignored the insult.\~ It came after all from a semi-educated dolt.\~ "You can hear him shifting cargo," Igan said.\~ He leaned across Harvey, pounded a palm against the compartment's side.\~ "What's going on out there?"
\par "Oh, sit down," Harvey said.\~ He put a hand on Igan's chest, pushed.\~ The surgeon stumbled backward onto the opposite bench.
\par Igan started to bounce back, his face dark, eyes glaring.\~ Boumour restrained him, rumbled, "Serenity, friend Igan."
\par Igan settled back.\~ Slowly, a look of patience came over his features.\~ "It's odd," he said, "how one's emotions have a way of asserting themselves in spite of --"
\par "That will pass," Boumour said.
\par Harvey found Lizbeth's hand, clutched it, signaled, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Igan's chest}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295  -- }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 it's convex and hard as plasmeld.\~ I felt it under his jacket."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "You think he's Cyborg?"}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "He breathes normally."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "And he has emotions.\~ I read fear on him."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Yes .\~.\~. but .\~.\~."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "We will be careful."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Boumour said, "You should place more trust in us, Durant.\~ Doctor Igan had deduced that our driver would not be moving cargo unless certain sounds were safe."
\par "How do we know who's moving cargo?" Harvey asked.
\par A look of caution fled across Boumour's massive calm.
\par Harvey read it, smiled.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Harvey!" }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Lizbeth said.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "You don't think the --"
}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "It's our driver out there," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Harvey reassured her.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "I can smell the wilderness in the air.\~ There's been no sound of a struggle.\~ One doesn't take a Cyborg without a struggle."}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "But where are we?" }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 she asked.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "In the mountains, the wilderness," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Harvey said.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "From the feel of the ride, we're well off the main by-ways."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Abruptly, their compartment lurched, slid sideways.\~ The single light was extinguished.\~ In the sudden darkness, the wall behind Harvey dropped away.\~ He clutched Lizbeth, whirled, found himself looking out into darkness .\~.\~. moonlight .\~.\~
. their driver a blocky shadow against a distant panorama of the megalopolis with its shimmering networks of light.\~ The moon silvered t
he tops of trees below them and there was a sharp smell of forest duff, resinous, dank, churned up by the van and not yet settled.\~ The wilderness lay silent as though waiting, analyzing the intrusion.
\par "Out," the driver said.
\par The Cyborg turned.\~ Harvey saw the features suddenly illuminated by moonlight, said, "Glisson!"
\par "Greetings, Durant," Glisson said.
\par "Why you?" Harvey asked.
\par "Why not?" Glisson asked.\~ "Get out of there now."
\par Harvey said:\~ "But my wife isn't --"
\par "I know about your wife, Durant.\~ She's had plenty of time since the treatment.\~ She can walk if she doesn't exert herself."
\par Igan spoke at Harvey's ear, "She'll be quite all right.\~ Sit her up gently and help her down."
\par "I .\~.\~. feel all right," Lizbeth said.\~ "Here."\~ She put an arm over Harvey's shoulder.\~ Together, they slid down to the ground.
\par Igan followed, asked, "Where are we?"
\par "We are someplace headed for someplace else," Glisson said.\~ "What is the condition of our prisoner?"
\par Boumour spoke from within the compartment, "He's coming around.\~ Help me lift him out."
\par "Why've we stopped?" Harvey asked.
\par "There is steep climbing ahead," Glisson said.\~ "We're dropping the load.\~ A van isn't built for this work."
\par Boumour and Igan shouldered past them carrying Svengaard, propped him against a stump beside the track.
\par "Wait here while I disengage the trailer," Glisson said.\~ "You might be considering whether we should abandon Svengaard."
\par Hearing his name, Svengaard opened his eyes, found himself staring out and down at the distant lights of the megalopolis.\~ His jaw ached where Harvey had struck him and there was a throbbing in his head.\~ He felt hungry, thirsty.\~
 His hands were numb beyond the bindings.\~ A dry smell of evergreen needles filled his nostrils.\~ He sneezed.
\par "Perhaps we }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 should }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 get rid of Svengaard," Igan said.
\par "I think not," Boumour said.\~ "He's a trained man, a possible ally.\~ We're going to need trained men."
\par Svengaard looked toward the voices.\~ They stood beside the van which was a long silvery shape behind a stubby double cab.\~ A wrenching of metal sounded there.\~
 The trailer slid backward on its skids almost two meters before stopping against a mound of dirt.
\par Glisson returned, squatted beside Svengaard.\~ "What is our decision?" asked the Cyborg.\~ "Kill him or keep him?"
\par Harvey gulped, felt Lizbeth clutch his arm.
\par "Keep him yet awhile," Boumour said.
\par "If he causes no more trouble," Igan said.
\par "We could always use his parts," Glisson said.\~ "Or try to grow a new Svengaard and retrain it."\~ The Cyborg stood.\~ "An immediate decision isn't necessary.\~ It is a thing to consider."
\par Svengaard remained silent, frozen by the emotionless clarity of the man's speech.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 A hard, brutal man, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he thought.\~ }
{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 A tough man, prepared for any violence.\~ A killer.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par "Into the cab with him then," Glisson said.\~ "Everyone into the cab.\~ We must get .\~.\~."\~ The Cyborg broke off, stared out toward the megalopolis.
\par Svengaard turned toward the strings of blue-white light glittering far away and cold.\~ A winking golden flare had appeared amidst the lights on his left.\~ 
Another blazed up beyond it -- a giant's bonfire set against the background of distant, moon-frosted mountains.\~ More yellow flares appeared to the right.\~ A bone-chilling rattle of sonics shook him, jarred a sympathetic metal dissonance from the van.

\par "What's happening?" Lizbeth hissed.
\par "Quiet!" Glisson said.\~ "Be quiet and observe."
\par "Gods of life," Lizbeth whispered, "what is it?"
\par "It is the death of a megalopolis," Boumour said.
\par Again, sonics rattled the van.
\par "That hurts," Lizbeth whimpered.
\par Harvey pulled her close, muttered, "Damn them!"
\par "Up here it hurts," Igan said, his voice chillingly formal.\~ "Down there it kills."
\par Green fog began emerging from the wilderness some ten kilometers below them.\~ It rolled out and down like a furious downy sea beneath the moon, engulfing everything -- hills, the gem-like lights, the yellow flares.
\par "Did you think they would use the death fog?" Boumour asked.
\par "We knew they would use it," Glisson said.
\par "I suppose so," Boumour said.\~ "Sterilize the area."
\par "What is it?" Harvey demanded.
\par "It comes from the vents where they administered the contraceptive gas," Boumour said.\~ "One particle on your skin -- the end of you."
\par Igan moved around, stared down at Svengaard.\~ "They are the ones who love us and care for us," he mocked.
\par "What's happening?" Svengaard asked.
\par "Can you not hear?" Igan asked.\~ "Can you not see?\~ Your friends the Optimen are sterilizing Seatac.\~ Did you have friends there?"
\par "Friends?"\~ There was a broken quality to Svengaard's voice.\~ He turned back to stare at the green fog.\~ The distant lights had all been extinguished.
\par Again, sonics chattered through them, shook the ground, rattled the van.
\par "What do you think of }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 them }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 now?" Igan asked.
\par Svengaard shook his head, unable to speak.\~ He wondered why he had no sensory fuse system to shut off this scene.\~ He felt chained to awareness through sense organs gone abnormal beyond any previous experience .\~.\~. a permissive aberration.\~ 
His senses were deceiving him, that was it.\~ This was a special case of self-deception.
\par "Why don't you answer me?" Igan asked.
\par "Leave him alone," Harvey said.\~ "We've griefs of our own.\~ Haven't you any feelings?"
\par "He sees it and does not believe," Igan said.
\par "How could they?" Lizbeth whispered.
\par "Self-preservation," Boumour rumbled.\~ "A trait our friend Svengaard doesn't seem to have.\~ Perhaps it was cut out of him."
\par Svengaard stared at the rolling green cloud.\~ So silent and stealthy it was.\~ The great reach of darkness where once there had been light and life filled him with a raw awareness of his own mortality.\~ 
He thought of friends down there -- the hospital staff -- embryos, his playmate-wife.
\par All destroyed.
\par Svengaard felt emptied, incapable of any emotion -- even grief.\~ He could only question, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 What was their purpose?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 

\par "Into the cab with him," Glisson said.\~ "On the floor in the rear."
\par Ungentle hands lifted Svengaard -- he identified Boumour and Glisson.\~ The driver's unemotional quality confused Svengaard.\~ He had never before encountered quite that abstract detachment in a human being.
\par They pushed him onto the floor of the van's cab.\~ The sharp edge of a seat brace dug into his side.\~ Feet came in around him.\~ Someone put a foot on his stomach, recoiled.\~ The turbines came alive.\~ A door was slammed.\~ They glided into motion.

\par Svengaard sank into a kind of stupor.
\par Lizbeth seated above him heaved a deep sigh.\~ Hearing it, Svengaard was roused to a feeling of compassion for her, his first emotion since the shock of seeing the megalopolis die.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Why did they do it? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he asked himself.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Why?}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par In the darkness, Lizbeth gripped Harvey's hand.\~ She could see in an occasional patch of moonglow the outline of Glisson directly ahead of her.\~ The Cyborg's minimal movement, the sense of power in every action, filled her with growing disquiet.\~ 
The scar of her operation itched.\~ She wanted to scratch, but feared calling attention to herself.\~ The Courier Service had been a long time building its own organization, deceiving both the Cyborgs and the Optimen.\~ They'd done it partly th
rough self-effacement.\~ Now, in her fear, she sank back into that treatment.
\par Through their hands, Harvey signaled, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Boumour and Igan, I read them now.\~ They're }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 new }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Cyborgs.\~ Probably just a first linkage with implanted computers.\~ They're just learning the price, shedding their normal human emotional reactions, learning to counterfeit emotion."}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par She absorbed this, seeing them through Harvey's deduction.\~ He often read people better than she did.\~ She re-read what she had seen of the two surgeons.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Do you read it?" }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he signaled.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "You're right.\~ Yes."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "It means a total break with Central.\~ They can never go back."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "That explains Seatac," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 she signaled.\~ She began to tremble.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "And we can't trust them," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Harvey said.\~ He pressed her close, soothing her.
\par The van labored up through the foothills skirting open meadows, following ancient tracks, an occasional stream-bed.\~ 
Shortly before dawn, it swerved left down a firebreak and into a stand of pines and cedars, squeezed its way through a narrow lane there with its blowers kicking up a heavy cloud of forest duff behind.\~ 
Glisson pulled to a stop behind an old building, moss on its sides, small curtained windows.\~ Pseudo-ducks with a weedy patina and grass-grown signs that they hadn't been animated in years, made a short f
ile near the building -- pale moon-figures in the light of a single bulb high up under the building's eaves.
\par Turbines whined to silence.\~ They could hear then the hum of machinery and looking toward the sound saw the dull silver outline of a ventilator tower among the trees.
\par A door at the corner of the building opened.\~ A heavy-headed man with a big jaw, stoop-shouldered, emerged blowing his nose into a red handkerchief.\~ He looked old, his face a mask of subservience.
\par Glisson said, "It's the sign.\~ All is safe here .\~.\~. for the moment."\~ He slipped out, approached the old man, coughed.
\par "A lot of sickness around these days," the old man said.\~ His voice was as ancient as his face, wheezing, slurring the consonants.
\par "You're not the only one with troubles," Glisson said.
\par The old man straightened, shed the stooped look and subservient manner.\~ "S'pose you're wanting a hidey hole," he said.\~ "Don't know if it's safe here.\~ Don't even know if I oughta hide you."
\par "I will give the orders here," Glisson said.\~ "You will obey."
\par The old man studied Glisson a moment, then a look of anger washed over his face.\~ "You damn' Cyborgs!" he said.
\par "Hold your tongue," Glisson said, his voice flat.\~ "We need food, a safe place to spend the day.\~ I shall require your help in hiding this van.\~ You must know the surrounding terrain.\~ And you will arrange other transportation for us."
\par "Best cut it up and bury it," the old man said, his voice surly.\~ "Been a hornet's nest stirred up.\~ Guess you know that."
\par "We know," Glisson said.\~ He turned, beckoned to the van.\~ "Come along.\~ Bring Svengaard."
\par Presently, the others joined him.\~ Boumour and Igan supported Svengaard between them.\~ The bindings on Svengaard's feet had been released, but he appeared barely able to stand.\~ Lizbeth walked w
ith the bent-over care that said she wasn't sure her incision had healed despite the enzymic speed-up medication.
\par "We will lodge here during daylight," Glisson said.\~ "This man will direct you to quarters."
\par "What word from Seatac?" Igan asked.
\par Glisson looked at the old man, said, "Answer."
\par The oldster shrugged.\~ "Courier through here couple of hours ago.\~ Said no survivors."
\par "Any report on a Dr. Potter?" Svengaard croaked.
\par Glisson whirled, stared at Svengaard.
\par "Dunno," the old man said.\~ "What route he take?"
\par Igan cleared his throat, glanced at Glisson, then at the old man.\~ "Potter?\~ I believe he was in the group coming out by the power tubes."
\par The old man flicked a glance at the ventilator tower growing more distinct among the trees by the second as daylight crept across the mountains.\~ "Nobody come through the tubes," he said.\~
 "They shut off the ventilators and flooded the tubes with that gas first thing."\~ He looked at Igan, "Ventilators been going again for about three hours."
\par Glisson studied Svengaard, asked, "Why are you interested in Potter?"
\par Svengaard remained silent.
\par "Answer me!" Glisson ordered.
\par Svengaard tried to swallow.\~ His throat ached.\~ He felt driven into a corner.\~ Glisson's words enraged him.\~ Without warning, Svengaard lurched forward dragging Igan and Boumour, lashed out at Glisson with a foot.
\par The Cyborg dodged with a blurring movement, caught the foot, jerked Svengaard from the two surgeons, whirled, swung Svengaard wide and released him.\~ Svengaard landed on his back, skidded across the ground, stopped.\~ 
Before he could move, Glisson was standing over him.\~ Svengaard lay there sobbing.
\par "Why are you interested in Potter?" Glisson demanded.
\par "Go away, go away, go away!" Svengaard sobbed.
\par Glisson straightened, looked around at Igan and Boumour.\~ "You understand this?"
\par Igan shrugged.\~ "It's emotion."
\par "Perhaps a shock reaction," Boumour said.
\par Through their hands, Harvey signaled Lizbeth, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "He's been in shock, but this mean's he's coming out of it.\~ These are medical people!\~ Can't they read }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 anything?"
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Glisson reads it," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 she answered.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
"He was testing them."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Glisson turned around, looked squarely at Harvey.\~ The bold understanding in the Cyborg's eyes shot a pang of fear through Harvey.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "Careful," }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Lizbeth signaled.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 "He's susp
icious of us."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par "Take Svengaard inside," Glisson said.
\par Svengaard looked up at their driver.\~ Glisson, the Durants called him.\~ But the old man from the building had labeled Glisson a Cyborg.\~ Was it possible?\~ Were the half-men being revived to challenge the Optimen once more?\~ 
Was that the reason for Seatac's death?
\par Boumour and Igan lifted him, checked the fetters on his hands.\~ "Let's have no more foolishness," Boumour said.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Are they like Glisson? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Svengaard asked himself.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
Are they, too, part man, part machine?\~ And what about the Durants?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 
\par Svengaard could feel the tear dampness in his eyes.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Hysteria, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he thought.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 Coming out of shock.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 He began to wonder at himself then with an odd feeling of guilt.\~ 
Why does Potter's death strike me more deeply than the death of an entire megalopolis, the extinction of my wife and friends?\~ What did Potter symbolize to me?
\par Boumour and Igan half carried, half walked him into the building, down a narrow hall and into a poorly lighted, gloomy big room with a ceiling that went up to bare beams two stories above.\~ 
They dropped him onto a dusty couch -- bare plastic and hydraulic contour-shapers that adjusted reluctantly.\~ The light came from two glowglobes high up under the beams.\~ It exposed oddments of furniture scattered aroun
d the room and mounds of strange shapes covered by slick, glistening fabric.\~ A table to his left, he realized, was made of planks.\~ Wood!\~ A contour cot lay beyond it, and an ancient roll-top desk with a missing drawer, and mismatched chairs.\~ 
A stained, soot-blackened fireplace, with an iron crane reaching across its mouth like a gibbet, occupied half the wall across from him.\~ The entire room smelled of dampness and rot.\~ The floor creaked as people moved.\~ Wood flooring!
\par Svengaard looked up at tiny windows admitting a sparse gray daylight that grew brighter by the second.\~ Even at its brightest he knew it wouldn't dispel the gloom of this place.\~ 
Here was sadness that made him think of people without number -- dead, forgotten.\~ Tears rolled down his cheeks.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 What's wrong with me? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 he wondered.
\par There came a sound from the yard of the van's turbines being ignited.\~ He heard it lift, leave .\~.\~. fade away.\~ Harvey and Lizbeth entered the room.
\par Lizbeth looked at Svengaard, then at Boumour and Igan who had taken up vigil on the cot.\~ With her crouched, protective walk, she crossed to Svengaard, touched his shoulder.\~ 
She saw his tears, evidence of humanity, and she wished then that he were her doctor.\~ Perhaps there was a way.\~ She decided to ask Harvey.
\par "Please trust us," she said.\~ "We won't harm you.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 They }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid14187295\charrsid14187295 are the ones who killed your wife and friends, not us."

\par }{\insrsid14187295 Svengaard pulled away.
\par }{\i\insrsid14187295 How dare she have pity on me? }{\insrsid14187295 he thought.\~ But she had reached some chord in him.\~ He could feel himself shattering.
\par Oppressive silence settled over the room.
\par Harvey came up, guided his wife to a chair at the table.
\par "It's wood," she said, touching the surface, wonder in her voice.\~ Then, "Harvey, I'm very hungry."
\par "They'll bring food as soon as they've disposed of the van," he said.
\par She clutched his hand and Svengaard watched, fascinated by the nervous movement of her fingers.
\par Glisson and the old man returned presently, slamming the door behind them.\~ The building creaked with their movement.
\par "We'll have a forest patrol vehicle for the next stage," Glisson said.\~ "Much safer.\~ There's a thing you all should know now."\~ The Cyborg moved a cold, weighted stare from face to face.\~
 "There was a marker on top of the van's load section which we abandoned last night."
\par "Marker?" Lizbeth said.
\par "A device for tracing us, following us," Glisson said.
\par "Ohhh!"\~ Lizbeth put a hand over her mouth.
\par "I do not know how closely they were following," Glisson said.\~ "I was altered for this task and certain of my devices were left behind.\~ They may know where we are right now."
\par Harvey shook his head.\~ "But why .\~.\~. ?"
\par "Why haven't they moved against us?" Glisson asked.\~ "It's obvious.\~ They hope we'll lead them to the vitals of our organization."\~ Something like rage came into the Cyborg's features.\~ "It may be we can surprise them."
