\par }\pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\insrsid14187295 
In the Survey Room, the great globe's instrumented inner walls lay relatively quiescent.\~ Calapine and Schruille of the Tuyere occupied the triple thrones.\~ The dais turned slowly, allowing them to scan the entire surface.\~
 Kaleidoscopic colors from the instruments played a somnolent visible melody across Calapine's features -- a wash of greens, reds, purples.
\par She felt tired with a definite emotion of self-pity.\~ There was something wrong with the enzymic analyzers.\~ She felt sure of it, wondering if the Underground had somehow compromised the function of the pharmacy computers.
\par Schruille was no help.\~ He'd laughed at the suggestion.
\par Allgood's features appeared on a call screen before Calapine.\~ She stopped the turning dais as he bowed, said, "I call to report, Calapine."\~ She noted the dark circles under his eyes, the drugged awareness in the way he held his head stiffly erect.

\par "You have found them?" Calapine asked.
\par "They're somewhere in the wilderness area, Calapine," Allgood said.\~ "They have to be in there."
\par "Have to be!" she sneered.\~ "You're a foolish optimist, Max."
\par "We know some of the hiding places they could've chosen, Calapine."
\par "For every one you know, they've nine you don't know," she said.
\par "I have the entire area ringed, Calapine.\~ We're moving in slowly, checking everywhere as we go.\~ They're there and we'll find them."
\par "He babbles," she said, glancing at Schruille.
\par Schruille returned a mirthless smile, looked at Allgood through the prismatic reflector.\~ "Max, have you found the source of the substitute embryo?"
\par "Not yet, Schruille."
\par He stared up at them, his face betraying his obvious confusion at the militancy and violence of }{\i\insrsid14187295 his }{\insrsid14187295 Optimen.
\par "Do you seek in Seatac?" Calapine demanded.
\par Allgood wet his lips with his tongue.
\par "Out with it!" she snapped.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 Ahhh, the fear in his eyes.}{\insrsid14187295 
\par "We're searching there, Calapine, but the --"
\par "You think we were too precipitate?" she asked.
\par He shook his head.
\par "You're acting strangely," Schruille said.\~ "Are you afraid of us?"
\par He hesitated, then, "Yes, Schruille."
\par "Yes, Schruille!" Calapine mimicked.
\par Allgood looked at her, the fear in his eyes tempered by anger.\~ "I'm taking every action I know, Calapine."
\par She marked a sudden precision in his manner behind the anger.\~ Her eyes went wide with wonder.\~ Was it possible?\~ She looked at Schruille, wondering if he had seen it.
\par "Max, why did you call us?" Schruille asked.
\par "I .\~.\~. to report, Schruille."
\par "You've reported nothing."
\par Hesitantly, Calapine brought up her instruments for a special probe of Allgood, stared at the result.\~ Horror mingled with rage in her.\~ Cyborg!\~ They had defiled Max!\~ Her Max!
\par "There's only need for you to obey us," Schruille said.
\par Allgood nodded, remained silent.
\par "You!" Calapine hissed.\~ She leaned toward the screen.\~ "You dared!\~ Why?\~ Why, Max?"
\par Schruille said, "What .\~.\~. ?"
\par But in the shocked instant of her questions, Allgood had seen that he was discovered.\~ He knew it was his end, could see it in her eyes.\~ "I saw .\~.\~. I found the dopplegangers," he stammered.
\par An angry twist of her hand rolled one of the rings on her throne arm.\~ Sonics sent a shock wave chattering across Allgood, blurred his image.\~ His lips moved soundlessly, eyes staring.\~ He collapsed.
\par "Why did you do that?" Schruille asked.
\par "He was Cyborg!" she grated, and pointed to the evidence of the instruments.
\par "Max?\~ Our Max?"\~ He looked at the instruments, nodded.
\par }{\i\insrsid14187295 "My }{\insrsid14187295 Max," she said.
\par "But he worshipped you, loved you."
\par "He does nothing now," she whispered.\~ She blanked the screen, continued to stare at it.\~ Already, the incident was receding from her mind.
\par "Do you enjoy direct action?" Schruille asked.
\par She met his gaze in the reflector.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 Enjoy direct action?\~ There was indeed a kind of elation in .\~.\~. violence.}{\insrsid14187295 
\par "We have no Max now," Schruille said.
\par "We'll waken another doppleganger," she said.\~ "Security can function without him for now."
\par "Who'll waken the doppleganger?" Schruille asked.\~ "Igan and Boumour are no longer with us.\~ The pharmacist, Hand, is gone."
\par "What's keeping Nourse?" she asked.
\par "Enzymic trouble," Schruille said, a note of glee in his voice.\~ "He said something about a necessary realignment of his prescription.\~ Bonellia hormone derivatives, I believe."
\par "Nourse can awaken the doppleganger," she said.\~ She wondered momentarily then why they needed the doppleganger.\~ Oh, yes.\~ Max was gone.
\par "There's more to it than merely awakening Max's duplicate," Schruille said.\~ "They're not as good as they once were, you know.\~ The new Max must be educated for his role, fitted into it gently.\~ It could be weeks .\~.\~. months."
\par "Then one of us can run Security," she said.
\par "You think we're ready for it?" Schruille asked.
\par "There's a }{\i\insrsid14187295 thrill }{\insrsid14187295 in this sort of decision-making," she said.\~ "I don't mind saying I've been deeply bored during the past several hundred years.\~ But now -- now, I feel alive, vital, alert, fascinated."\~
 She looked up at the glowing banks of scanner eyes, a full band of them, showing their fellow Optimen watching activities in the Survey Room.\~ "And I'm not alone in this."
\par Schruille glanced up at the glittering arctic circle of the globe's inner wall.\~ "Aliveness," he murmured.\~ "But Max .\~.\~. he is dead."
\par She remembered then, said, "Any Max can be replaced."\~ She looked at Schruille, turning her head to stare past the prism.\~ "You're very blunt today, Schruille.\~ You've spoken of death twice that I recall."
\par "Blunt?\~ I?"\~ He shook his head.\~ "But I didn't }{\i\insrsid14187295 erase }{\insrsid14187295 Max."
\par She laughed aloud.\~ "My own reactions thrill me, Schruille!"
\par "And do you find changes in your enzymic demands?"
\par "A few.\~ What is that?\~ Times change.\~ It's part of being.\~ Adjustments must be made."
\par "Indeed," he said.
\par "Where'd they find a substitute for the Durant embryo?" she asked, her mind shooting off at a tangent.
\par "Perhaps the new Max can discover," Schruille said.
\par "He must."
\par "Or you will grow another Max?" Schruille said.
\par "Don't mock me, Schruille."
\par "I wouldn't dare."
\par Again, she looked directly at him.
\par "What if they produced their own embryo for the substitution?" Schruille asked.
\par She turned away.\~ "In the name of all that's proper, how?"
\par "Air can be filtered clean of contraceptive gas," Schruille said.
\par "You're disgusting!"
\par "Am I?\~ But haven't you wondered what Potter concealed?"
\par "Potter?\~ We know what he concealed."
\par "A person devoted to the preservation of life .\~.\~. such as that is," Schruille said.\~ "What did he hide in his mind?"
\par "Potter is no more."
\par "But what did he conceal?"
\par "You think he knew the source of the .\~.\~. outside interference?"
\par "Perhaps.\~ And }{\i\insrsid14187295 he }{\insrsid14187295 would know where to find an embryo."
\par "Then the record will show the source, as you said yourself."
\par "I've been reconsidering."
\par She stared at him in the prism.\~ "It's not possible."
\par "That I could reconsider?"
\par "You know what I mean -- what you're thinking."
\par "But it is }{\i\insrsid14187295 possible."}{\insrsid14187295 
\par "It isn't!"
\par "You're being stubborn, Cal.\~ A female should be the last person to deny such a possibility."
\par "Now, you're being truly disgusting!"
\par "We know Potter found a self-viable," Schruille pressed.\~ "They could have many self-viables -- male and female.\~ We know historically the capabilities of such raw union.\~ It's part of our }{\i\insrsid14187295 natural }{\insrsid14187295 ancestry."

\par "You're unspeakable," she breathed.
\par "You can face the concept of death but not this," Schruille said.\~ "Most interesting."
\par "Disgusting!" she barked.
\par "But possible," Schruille said.
\par "The substitute embryo wasn't self-viable!" she pounced.
\par "All the more reason they might've been willing to sacrifice it for one that was, eh?"
\par "Where would they find the vat facilities, the chemicals, the enzymes, the --"
\par "Where they've always been."
\par "What?"
\par "They've put the Durant embryo back into its mother," Schruille said.\~ "We can be certain of this.\~ Would it not be equally logical to leave the embryo there to begin with -- never remove it, never isolate the gametes in a vat at all?"
\par Calapine found herself speechless.\~ She sensed a sour taste in her mouth, realized with a feeling of shock that she wanted to vomit.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 Something's wrong with my enzyme balance, }{\insrsid14187295 she thought.
\par She spoke slowly, precisely, "I am reporting to pharmacy at once, Schruille.\~ I do not feel well."
\par "By all means," Schruille said.\~ He glanced up and around at the watching scanners -- a full circle of them.
\par Delicately, Calapine eased herself out of her throne, slid down the beam to the lock segment.\~ Before letting herself out, she cast a look up at the dais, faintly remembering.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 Which Max was .\~.\~. erased? }{\insrsid14187295 
she asked herself.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 We've had many of him .\~.\~. a successful model for our Security.\~ }{\insrsid14187295 She thought of the others, Max after Max after Max, each shunted aside when his appearance began to annoy his masters.\~
 They stretched into infinity, images in an endless system of mirrors.
\par }{\i\insrsid14187295 What is erasure to such as Max? }{\insrsid14187295 she wondered.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 I am an unbroken continuity of existence.\~ But a doppleganger doesn't remember.\~ A doppleganger breaks the continuity.}{\insrsid14187295 
\par }{\i\insrsid14187295 Unless the cells remember.}{\insrsid14187295 
\par Memory .\~.\~. cells .\~.\~. embryos .\~.\~.
\par She thought of the embryo within Lizbeth Durant.\~ Disgusting, but simple.\~ So beautifully simple.\~ Her gorge began to rise.\~ Whirling, Calapine dropped down to the Hall of Counsel, ran for the nearest pharmacy outlet.\~
 As she ran, she clenched the hand that had slain Max and helped destroy a megalopolis.
