\par }\pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\insrsid14187295 "There, it is done," Calapine said.
\par She looked at Schruille and Nourse in the reflectors.
\par Schruille indicated the kinesthetic analogue relays of the Survey Globe's inner wall.\~ "Did you observe Svengaard's emotion?"
\par "He was properly horrified," Calapine said.
\par Schruille pursed his lips, studied her reflection.\~ A session with the pharmacy had restored her composure, but she occupied her throne in a subdued mood.\~ The kaleidoscopic play of lights from the wall gave an unhealthy cast to her skin.\~
 There was a definite flush to her features.
\par Nourse glanced up at the observer lights -- the span of arctic wall glowed with a dull red intensity, every position occupied.\~ With hardly an exception, the Optiman community watched developments.
\par "We have a decision to make," Nourse said.
\par "You look pale, Nourse," Calapine said.\~ "Did you have pharmacy trouble?"
\par "No more than you."\~ He spoke defensively.\~ "A simple enzymic heterodyning.\~ It's pretty well damped out."
\par "I say bring them here now," Schruille said.
\par "To what purpose?" Nourse asked.\~ "We have the pattern of their flight very well fixed.\~ Why let them escape again?"
\par "I don't like the thought of unregistered self-viables -- who knows how many -- running loose out there," Schruille said.
\par "Are you sure we could take them alive?" Calapine asked.
\par "The Cyborg admits ineffectiveness against us," Schruille said.
\par "Unless that's a trick," Nourse said.
\par "I don't think so," Calapine said.\~ "And once we have them here we can extract the information we need from their raw brains with the utmost precision."
\par Nourse turned, stared at her.\~ He couldn't understand what had happened to Calapine.\~ She spoke with the callous brutality of a Folk woman.\~ She was like an awakened ghoul, as though violence were her rising bell.
\par }{\i\insrsid14187295 What is her setting bell? }{\insrsid14187295 he wondered.\~ And he was shocked at his own thought.
\par "If they have means of destroying themselves?" Nourse asked.\~ "I remind you of the computer nurse and a sad number of our own surgeons who appear to be in league with these criminals.\~ We were powerless to prevent their self-destruction."
\par "How callous you are, Nourse," Calapine said.
\par "Callous?\~ I?"\~ He shook his head.\~ "I merely wish to prevent further pain.\~ Let us destroy them ourselves and go on from here."
\par "Glisson's a full Cyborg," Schruille said.\~ "Can you imagine what his memory banks would reveal?"
\par "I remember the one who escorted Potter," Nourse said.\~ "Let us take no risk.\~ His quietude could be a trick."
\par "A contact narcotic in their present cell," Schruille said.\~ "That's my suggestion."
\par "How do you know it'll work on the Cyborgs?" Nourse asked.
\par "Then they could escape once more," Schruille said.\~ He shrugged.\~ "What does it matter?"
\par "Into another megalopolis," Nourse said.\~ "Is that it?"
\par "We know the infection's widespread," Schruille said.\~ "Certainly, there were cells right here in Central.\~ We've cleaned out those, but the --"
\par "I say stop them now!" Nourse snapped.
\par "I agree with Schruille," Calapine said.\~ "What's the risk?"
\par "The sooner we stop them the sooner we can return to our own pursuits," Nourse said.
\par "This }{\i\insrsid14187295 is }{\insrsid14187295 our pursuit," Schruille said.
\par "You like the idea of sterilizing another megalopolis, don't you, Schruille?" Nourse sneered.\~ "Which one this time?\~ How about Loovil?"
\par "Once was enough," Schruille said.\~ "But likes and dislikes really have nothing to do with it."
\par "Let us put it to a vote then," Calapine said.
\par "Because you're two to one against me, eh?" Nourse said.
\par "She means a }{\i\insrsid14187295 full }{\insrsid14187295 vote," Schruille said.\~ He looked up at the observation lights.\~ "We've obviously a full quorum."
\par Nourse stared at the indicators knowing he'd been neatly trapped.\~ He dared not protest a full vote -- any vote.\~ And his two companions appeared so sure of themselves.\~ }{\i\insrsid14187295 "This is our pursuit."}{\insrsid14187295 
\par "We've allowed the Cyborgs to interfere," Nourse said, "because they increased the proportion of viables in the genetic reserve.\~ Did we do this merely to destroy the genetic reserve?"
\par Schruille indicated a bank of binary pyramids on the Globe's wall.\~ "If they endanger us, certainly.\~ But the issue is unregistered }{\i\insrsid14187295 self}{\insrsid14187295 -viables, their possible immunity to the contraceptive gas.\~ Wher
e else could they have produced the substitute embryo?"
\par "If it comes down to it, we don't need any of them," Calapine said.
\par "Destroy them all?" Nourse asked.\~ "All the Folk?"
\par "And raise a new crop of dopplegangers," she said.\~ "Why not?"
\par "Duplicates don't always come true," Nourse said.
\par "Nothing limits us," Schruille said.
\par "Our sun isn't infinite," Nourse said.
\par "We'll solve that when the need arises," Calapine said.\~ "What problem can defy us?\~ We're not limited by time."
\par "Yet we're sterile," Nourse said.\~ "Our gametes refuse to unite."
\par "And well they do," Schruille said.\~ "I'd not have it otherwise."
\par "All we wish now is a simple vote," Calapine said.\~ "A simple vote on whether to capture and bring in one tiny band of criminals.\~ Why should that arouse major debate?"
\par Nourse started to speak, thought better of it.\~ He shook his head, looked from Calapine to Schruille.
\par "Well?" Schruille asked.
\par "I think this little band is the real issue," Nourse said.\~ "One Sterrie surgeon, two Cyborgs and two viables."
\par "And Durant was ready to kill the Sterrie," Schruille said.
\par "No."\~ It was Calapine.\~ "He wasn't ready to erase anyone."\~ She found herself suddenly interested in the train of Nourse's reasoning.\~ It was his logic and reason, after all, which had always attracted her.
\par Schruille, seeing her waver, said, "Calapine!"
\par "We all saw Durant's emotions," Nourse said.\~ He waved at the instrument wall in front of him.\~ "He would've killed no one.\~ He was .\~.\~. }{\i\insrsid14187295 educating }{\insrsid14187295 Svengaard, talking to Svengaard with his hands."
\par "As they do between themselves, he and his wife," Calapine said.\~ "Certainly!"
\par "You say we should raise a new crop of dopplegangers."\~ Nourse said.\~ "Which seed shall we use?\~ The occupants of Seatac, perhaps?"
\par "We could take the seed cells first," Schruille said, and he wondered how he had been put so suddenly on the defensive.\~ "I say let's vote on it.\~ Bring them here for full interrogation or destroy them."
\par "No need," Nourse said.\~ "I've changed my mind.\~ Bring them here .\~.\~. if you can."
\par "Then it's settled," Schruille said.\~ He rapped the signal into his throne arm.\~ "You see, it's really very simple."
\par "Indeed?" Nourse said.\~ "Then why do Calapine and I find ourselves suddenly reluctant to use violence?\~ Why do we long for the old ways when Max shielded us from ourselves?"
